AI-Based Real-Time Surgical Tool Tracking with Dynamic Danger Zone Alerting



Abstract—
The integration of artificial intelligence in surgical environments has the potential to significantly enhance intraoperative safety and decision-making. This paper presents a real-time system for surgical tool tracking and proximity-based risk alerting using deep learning and computer vision techniques. The proposed framework utilizes the YOLOv8 for detecting surgical instruments in video streams, followed by a tracking mechanism to maintain temporal consistency across frames. A predefined critical region, referred to as the “danger zone,” is modeled using a polygonal mask. The system computes the spatial distance between detected tools and the danger zone using geometric analysis, enabling continuous risk assessment.

To improve reliability, temporal smoothing techniques are applied to reduce false-positive alerts caused by detection noise. When the proximity of a tool to the critical region falls below a predefined threshold, the system generates a real-time visual warning overlay. Experimental results on simulated surgical video data demonstrate the feasibility of the proposed approach in achieving stable and responsive alerting behavior. The system is lightweight, deployable on standard computing hardware, and suitable for real-time applications.

The proposed framework highlights the potential of combining object detection, tracking, and spatial reasoning to develop intelligent safety-assist systems in surgical settings.

Keywords— Computer Vision, Surgical Tool Tracking, Real-Time Systems, Deep Learning, Safety Monitoring, Proximity Analysis

Research Gap Paragraph (ready to paste)
Despite significant advancements in computer vision for surgical environments, existing research has primarily focused on surgical tool detection, segmentation, and tracking using deep learning models such as YOLOv8. While these approaches achieve high accuracy under controlled conditions, they largely emphasize visual recognition tasks rather than context-aware safety applications. In particular, there is limited work on integrating spatial proximity analysis and real-time alert mechanisms to assist surgeons during procedures. Most current systems do not quantify the relative distance between surgical instruments and critical anatomical regions, nor do they provide dynamic, interpretable warnings based on risk thresholds. Furthermore, existing solutions often lack lightweight, deployable architectures suitable for real-time processing in resource-constrained environments.

To address these limitations, this project proposes a real-time surgical safety monitoring framework that combines object detection, multi-object tracking, and proximity-based risk assessment. By introducing a dynamic “danger zone” model and continuous distance estimation, the system aims to enhance intraoperative awareness and reduce the risk of accidental damage to critical structures.



🧠 AI-Based Real-Time Surgical Tool Tracking with Dynamic Danger Zone Alerting


📌 Overview
This project presents a real-time computer vision system designed to enhance surgical safety by detecting and tracking surgical tools in video streams and generating alerts when tools approach predefined critical regions (“danger zones”).

The system leverages deep learning-based object detection using YOLOv8 and integrates spatial analysis to perform proximity-based risk assessment.

🎯 Objectives
Detect surgical tools in real-time video
Track tool movement across frames
Define and monitor critical regions (danger zones)
Compute distance between tools and danger zones
Trigger visual alerts when risk thresholds are exceeded
